  <h1>CMA Dishmachines Repair — Los Angeles &amp; Southern California</h1>

  <p>CMA Dishmachines is a Southern California company — they've been manufacturing commercial dishwashers in Garden Grove since the early 1970s. That's about 15 miles from Downtown LA. In a field where most commercial dishwasher brands are German, Italian, or from the American Midwest, CMA is genuinely local. They're part of Ali Group, the Italian holding company that also owns Champion Industries — which means when we're sourcing parts for CMA equipment, we're working through the same parts network we use for Champion, with strong availability on common components.</p>

  <p>CMA's engineering philosophy is deliberately different from most European commercial dishwashers: they use electro-mechanical controls rather than electronic control boards. This isn't a limitation — it's a design choice. Electro-mechanical controls are simpler to diagnose in the field, more tolerant of the heat and moisture environment inside a commercial kitchen, and the replacement parts are significantly less expensive than control boards from Winterhalter or Meiko. When a CMA-180 has a problem, the fault is usually traceable to a specific mechanical or electro-mechanical component rather than a failed board that costs $400 to replace. We stock CMA parts specifically because this makes same-day resolution realistic on most calls.</p>

  <p>$120 commercial diagnostic applied to the repair. Same-day response throughout SoCal. Call <strong>{phone}</strong>.</p>

  <h2>CMA Equipment We Service</h2>

  <h3>CMA-180 Series — High-Temperature Door-Type Machines</h3>
  <p>The CMA-180 series is CMA's flagship — the high-temperature door-type machine that defines their product line. These machines use the Safe-T-Temp system: the machine will not release the door or complete the final rinse phase until the thermostat confirms the wash water has reached the sanitizing temperature. If the thermostat isn't satisfied within the cycle time, the machine holds rather than completing a potentially unsanitized load. This is genuinely useful from a food safety standpoint — the machine enforces its own compliance. The downside is that Safe-T-Temp failures present as "machine won't complete cycle" and operators assume the machine is broken when it's actually doing its job: holding because the thermostat is reading below spec due to scale on the heating element.</p>
  <p>The CMA-180 series comes in several configurations: the standard door-type (CMA-180), undercounter (CMA-180UC), ventless variants (CMA-180VLT, CMA-180VL), and open-side models for high-volume throughput. The ventless models are common in LA's older restaurant buildings where installing a vent hood over the dishwasher isn't practical — same application as the DH6000 from Champion. In LA hard water, the ventless heat exchanger on CMA ventless models scales the same way as on any other ventless commercial dishwasher: quarterly descaling minimum.</p>
  <p><strong>Models:</strong> CMA-180, CMA-180S, CMA-180UC, CMA-180SB, CMA-180VLT, CMA-180VL, CMA-180OS, CMA-180CB, CMA-180T, CMA-180WS, CMA-200, CMA-250, CMA-260, CMA-270</p>

  <h3>CMA-L1X Series — Conveyor Dishwashers</h3>
  <p>CMA's L1X conveyor series serves the high-volume operations — hotel banquet dishrooms, university dining, institutional cafeterias, and large restaurants in the SGV and South Bay where throughput matters more than premium brand recognition. The L1X uses CMA's rinse water recirculation design: water from the final rinse cycle is captured and used as the wash water for the next cycle, reducing per-rack water consumption to just over a gallon. For LA operators watching water bills and sustainability metrics, this is a real operational advantage.</p>
  <p>Conveyor CMA service patterns: zone curtain wear between wash sections (same as any conveyor — inspect quarterly), conveyor drive chain tension (monthly adjustment in heavy-use operations), and chemical injector calibration on low-temperature L1X variants. The low-temperature L1X models use chemical sanitizer injection — the injector pump is the most common service call on these machines, and the symptom is dishes that pass visual inspection but fail sanitizer concentration testing during health inspections.</p>
  <p><strong>Models:</strong> CMA-L1X, CMA-L1XE, CMA-L1XLT, CMA-L1XLE, CMA-L1XH, CMA-L1XLTE, CMA-L1XLHE, CMA-AH, CMA-DS</p>

  <h3>CMA Glasswashers &amp; Specialty</h3>
  <p>CMA's GL glasswasher series is in bar service throughout LA — the same bar and QSR segment where Jackson TempStar and Beverage-Air back bar coolers are common. CMA glasswashers use the same electro-mechanical controls as the full-size machines — simpler to service, easier to get same-day resolution. The scullery series (CMA-EST, large-opening scullery models) handles the larger items — sheet pans, stock pots, hotel pans — that standard 20×20-inch rack machines can't fit. The PT-15 pan washer is a specialty machine for kitchens doing high volume sheet pan and pot washing.</p>
  <p><strong>Models:</strong> CMA-GL, CMA-UC50, CMA-UC65, CMA-UC85, CMA-EST, CMA-AH, PT-15, CMA-400, CMA-600</p>

  <h2>The Safe-T-Temp System — Most Common CMA Misdiagnosis</h2>

  <p>Safe-T-Temp is the feature that generates the most confused service calls on CMA-180 machines. The system works like this: at the end of the wash cycle, the machine initiates the final rinse. If the thermostat — mounted in the wash tank — hasn't confirmed that water temperature reached 180°F by the time the rinse completes, the machine holds. Door stays locked. Machine won't cycle. Operator assumes it's broken.</p>

  <p>In most of these calls, the machine is working exactly as designed. What's failing is heat transfer to the thermostat probe — usually because the probe has scale deposits from LA hard water that insulate it from the water temperature. The water may actually be at or near 180°F, but the probe is reading lower because scale is thermally insulating it. The fix: descale the probe and the heating element, verify temperature with an independent thermometer, confirm Safe-T-Temp is triggering correctly. Not a board failure. Not a thermostat failure. Scale on a $15 probe.</p>

  <p>We check Safe-T-Temp probe scale on every CMA-180 call where the presenting complaint is "won't complete cycle" or "door won't open." It's the first diagnostic step, not the last.</p>

  <h2>Recent CMA Service Calls</h2>

  <h3>"CMA-180 won't complete cycle — Safe-T-Temp holding, restaurant Koreatown"</h3>
  <p>Korean BBQ restaurant, CMA-180 locking up after every wash cycle — machine wouldn't release the door to start the next load. Operator had called another company who quoted a thermostat replacement at $280. We arrived and checked the Safe-T-Temp probe first: heavy scale coating on the probe surface, classic LA hard water pattern. Water in the tank was measuring 182°F on our calibrated thermometer — well above the 180°F threshold — but the probe was reading 171°F through its scale layer. Machine was holding correctly based on what the probe was telling it. Descaled the probe with CMA-approved agent, wipe-tested the probe surface clean, verified Safe-T-Temp triggering correctly at 181°F probe reading. Machine back to normal operation in 45 minutes. No parts needed.</p>

  <h3>"CMA-L1X conveyor — failing sanitizer test, school cafeteria Inglewood"</h3>
  <p>Low-temperature CMA-L1X at a school cafeteria — health inspector had flagged inadequate sanitizer concentration in the final rinse. Machine was cycling normally, no error conditions. The chemical injector pump had worn — delivering about 40% of the specified sanitizer dose per rack. Dishes looked clean but the chlorine concentration in the rinse water was below the NSF requirement. Replaced the injector pump assembly, calibrated delivery rate with test strips at spec (100 ppm), verified through three consecutive cycles. Left the cafeteria manager with a weekly sanitizer concentration log — health code requires it for low-temp machines. They hadn't been logging. Two issues fixed on one visit.</p>

  <h3>"CMA-180VLT ventless — steam escaping, kitchen humidity up, West Hollywood bar"</h3>
  <p>Bar running a CMA-180VLT ventless machine — kitchen staff complaining about humidity building up during dishwashing. Machine had been installed specifically because the bar kitchen had no exhaust hood. The ventless heat exchanger had scaled from 8 months of LA water without descaling — same failure mode as Champion DH6000 and Meiko M-iClean ventless systems. Descaled the heat exchanger, verified exhaust air temperature and humidity at spec. Kitchen humidity returned to normal. Bar owner hadn't known the ventless exchanger needed separate maintenance — the install crew hadn't told them. We put a maintenance sticker on the machine: "Descale heat exchanger every 90 days in LA water."</p>

  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

  <p><strong>My CMA-180 won't complete its cycle — is it broken?</strong><br>
  Probably not. On CMA-180 series machines, the most common cause of a cycle that won't complete is the Safe-T-Temp system holding because the thermostat probe is reading below 180°F due to scale buildup. The machine is working correctly — it's refusing to complete an unsanitized load. Descaling the probe is usually the fix. Call {phone} for a same-day diagnosis before ordering any parts.</p>

  <p><strong>Why does CMA use electro-mechanical controls instead of electronic?</strong><br>
  It's a deliberate engineering choice. Electro-mechanical controls are more tolerant of the heat and moisture environment inside a commercial kitchen, simpler to diagnose in the field, and the replacement components cost significantly less than electronic control boards. For operators, it means lower repair costs and faster service resolution on most failures.</p>

  <p><strong>How often should CMA ventless models be descaled in Los Angeles?</strong><br>
  Every 90 days minimum for the ventless heat exchanger in LA water. The standard recommendation assumes lower water hardness than LA's 250–350 ppm TDS. Quarterly descaling on the heat exchanger prevents the steam management degradation that makes the kitchen humid and signals the exchanger is scaling up.</p>

  <p><strong>Do you carry OEM CMA parts?</strong><br>
  Yes — Safe-T-Temp thermostats, chemical injector pumps, door latch assemblies, heating elements, conveyor drive components, and spray arm assemblies for CMA-180, L1X, and glasswasher series. CMA is Ali Group, same parts network as Champion — good availability on most common components.</p>

  <p><strong>What is your diagnostic fee?</strong><br>
  $120 commercial diagnostic, applied to the repair when you proceed. What we quote on-site is what's on the invoice.</p>

